  "prompt": "What is achilles tendonitis?",
  "response": "Achilles tendonitis is an overuse injury of the Achilles tendon, the large tendon that runs down the back of your lower leg from your calf muscle to your heel bone. It's characterized by pain, swelling, and stiffness along this tendon, typically near the heel.\n\nHere's a breakdown:\n\n*   **Achilles Tendon:** This is the strongest tendon in the body, crucial for walking, running, jumping, and standing on your toes. It connects the calf muscles (gastrocnemius and soleus) to the heel bone (calcaneus).\n\n*   **Tendonitis vs. Tendinosis:**  It's important to note that the term \"tendonitis\" implies inflammation, but chronic Achilles problems often involve tendinosis, which refers to degeneration of the tendon's collagen. Many cases are a combination of both, so the term \"tendinopathy\" is sometimes used to encompass both conditions.\n\n*   **Causes:** The primary cause is repetitive strain and overuse. Factors contributing to Achilles tendonitis include:\n\n    *   **Sudden increase in activity:** Starting a new exercise program, increasing mileage too quickly, or intense workouts without proper conditioning.\n    *   **Tight calf muscles:** Restricts ankle motion and puts extra stress on the Achilles tendon.\n    *   **Inadequate stretching:** Failure to properly stretch calf muscles before and after exercise.\n    *   **Poor footwear:** Lack of support or cushioning can contribute.\n    *   **Overpronation:** Feet rolling inward excessively during walking or running can strain the tendon.\n    *   **Hill running or stair climbing:** Places extra stress on the Achilles tendon.\n    *   **Bone spurs:**  Heel spurs can rub against the tendon.\n    *   **Age:** As we age, tendons become less flexible and more prone to injury.\n    *   **Medical Conditions:** Certain conditions like psoriasis, high blood pressure, and obesity can increase risk.\n\n*   **Symptoms:**\n\n    *   **Pain:**  Aching, stiffness, or burning pain in the back of the heel and lower leg. The pain may be worse after exercise, in the morning, or after periods of inactivity.\n    *   **Swelling:**  A visible bump or swelling along the Achilles tendon.\n    *   **Stiffness:**  Stiffness in the ankle, especially in the morning.\n    *   **Tenderness:**  Pain when touching the Achilles tendon.\n    *   **Limited range of motion:** Difficulty pointing the toes or flexing the foot.\n    *   **Crepitus:**  A grating or crackling sound or sensation when moving the ankle.\n    *   **Weakness:**  Weakness when pushing off with the toes.\n\n*   **Diagnosis:**  A doctor can usually diagnose Achilles tendonitis with a physical examination.  Imaging tests, such as X-rays (to rule out other problems like fractures or bone spurs) or MRI (to assess the severity of the tendon damage), may be ordered.\n\n*   **Treatment:** The goal of treatment is to relieve pain and inflammation and to restore normal function of the Achilles tendon.  Treatment options include:\n\n    *   **Rest:** Avoid activities that aggravate the pain.\n    *   **Ice:** Apply ice packs to the affected area for 15-20 minutes several times a day.\n    *   **Compression:** Use a bandage to support the ankle and reduce swelling.\n    *   **Elevation:** Keep the leg elevated to reduce swelling.\n    *   **Pain relievers:** Over-the-counter pain relievers, such as ibuprofen or naproxen, can help reduce pain and inflammation.\n    *   **Physical therapy:** Stretching and strengthening exercises to improve flexibility and strength of the calf muscles and Achilles tendon. Eccentric exercises (slowly lowering the heel) are particularly effective.\n    *   **Orthotics:**  Custom or over-the-counter arch supports can help correct foot pronation and reduce stress on the tendon.\n    *   **Heel lifts:**  Temporary heel lifts can reduce stress on the tendon.\n    *   **Immobilization:**  In severe cases, a walking boot or cast may be necessary to immobilize the ankle and allow the tendon to heal.\n    *   **Injections:** Corticosteroid injections are generally not recommended due to the risk of tendon rupture.  Platelet-rich plasma (PRP) injections are sometimes used, but their effectiveness is still under investigation.\n    *   **Surgery:**  Surgery may be considered as a last resort if other treatments are not effective.  Surgical options include removing damaged tissue and repairing the tendon.\n\n*   **Prevention:**\n\n    *   **Gradual Progression:** Increase activity levels gradually to avoid overloading the tendon.\n    *   **Proper Warm-up and Cool-down:**  Always warm up before exercise and cool down afterward.\n    *   **Stretching:** Regularly stretch the calf muscles and Achilles tendon.\n    *   **Appropriate Footwear:** Wear shoes with good support and cushioning. Replace worn-out shoes.\n    *   **Strengthening:** Strengthen the calf muscles.\n    *   **Avoid Overuse:** Don't push yourself too hard, especially when starting a new activity.\n    *   **Listen to Your Body:** Stop if you feel pain.\n\nIt is important to consult with a healthcare professional for a proper diagnosis and treatment plan. Ignoring Achilles tendonitis can lead to chronic pain, decreased mobility, and even tendon rupture.\n",
